          "id": "medqa-d6ebf8a72c60d27e",
          "text": "An 80-year-old male with known metastatic prostate cancer presents to your office with vague complaints of \"achy bones.\" Strangely, he refers to you using the name of another physician. On physical exam, he is afebrile, but mildly tachycardic at 100 beats/min. Mucous membranes are dry. Cardiac exam shows regular rhythm and no murmurs. The patient has diffuse, nonfocal abdominal pain. He cannot articulate the correct date. You check the patient's serum calcium level, which is found to be 15.3 mg/dL. What is the best next step in management?",
